b'' b'' b' what is the objection to celebration of easter?' b'' b'the objection naturally is in the way in which you phrase it.' b'easter (or eashtar or ishtar or ishtarti or other spellings) is the pagan' b'whore goddess of fertility. therefore, your question to me is "what is' b'the objection to celebration of the pagan whore goddess?" when phrased' b'that way i suspect (or at least i would hope) that it becomes immeadiately' b'apparent what my objection to "celebrating" her would be.' b'' b' it is celebration of the resurrection of jesus.' b'' b'no, you are thinking perhaps of "ressurection sunday" i think.' b'(though i\'m not too crazy about the word "sunday", but i certainly like' b'this phrasing much better than envoking the name of the whore goddess.)' b'for that matter, stay biblical and call it omar rasheet (the feast of' b'first fruits). torah commands that this be observed on the day following' b'the sabbath of passover week. (sunday by any other name in modern' b'parlance.) why is there so much objection to observing the resurrection' b'on the 1st day of the week on which it actually occured? why jump it all' b'over the calendar the way easter does? why not just go with the sunday' b'following passover the way the bible has it? why seek after unbiblical' b'methods?' b'' b" i don't recall a command in scripture for us to celebrate" b' the resurrection, but it is the sole and only reason that' b' we are christians--how could we not celebrate it?' b'' b'so what does this question have to do with easter (the whore' b'goddess)? i am all for celebrating the resurrection. just keep that' b'whore out of the discussion.' b'' b' if it is only the name which is a problem, i suggest that if' b' we are too concerned about etymology, there are a lot of' b' words we are going to have to drop. (as an aside, some' b' terminally pc people here in ottawa want dictionaries to be' b' altered so that there are no negative definitions associated' b' with the word _black_, so a