eaning over time. the days of' b'the week are of course originally based on pagan gods. some' b'christians prefer to refer to "first day", "second day", etc. however' b'the majority of christians have not been persuaded. the question' b'seems to be whether it makes any difference what the dictionary shows' b'as the derivation of a word, if what people mean by it and think when' b'they use it is different.' b'' b"indeed i'd like to suggest that postings like this could themselves be" b'dangerous. suppose people in general use easter to mean the' b"celebration of christ's resurrection. postings trying to convince" b'them that they really mean a celebration in honor of some godess run' b'the risk of creating exactly the situation that they claim to oppose.' b"they are doing their best to *create* a linkage in people's minds" b"between their celebration and the pagan goddess. it's not clear that" b'this is a healthy thing.' b'' b'--clh]' 